fvfx.com/x-men-dark-phoenix/ |title=X-Men: Dark Phoenix |last=Frei |first=Vincent |date=September 27, 2018 |website=The Art of VFX |access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CondorCollider\">{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/lana-condor-interview-deadly-class-dark-phoenix/ |title=Lana Condor on Playing a \"Badass\" Assassin in ''Deadly Class'' & Not Returning for ''Dark Phoenix'' |website=Collider |last=Romano |first=Nick |date=January 7, 2019 |access-date=January 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/75FjJyysW/http://collider.com/lana-condor-interview-deadly-class-dark-phoenix/ |archive-date=January 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NoPsylocke\">{{cite web |url=https://etcanada.com/news/418694/olivia-munn-confirms-she-wont-appear-in-upcoming-x-men-sequel-im-not-in-it/ |title=Olivia Munn Confirms She Won't Appear in Upcoming ''X-Men'' Sequel: 'I'm Not In It' |website=ET Canada |last=Price |first=Chandra |date=February 12, 2019 |access-date=February 12, 2019 |archive-url=http://www.webcitation.org/768yBPqdG/https://etcanada.com/news/418694/olivia-munn-confirms-she-wont-appear-in-upcoming-x-men-sequel-im-not-in-it/ |archive-date=February 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Reviews1\">{{cite news |title=Dark Phoenix reviews roundup: Critics pan 'underwhelming' X-Men film starring Sophie Turner |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/x-men-dark-phoenix-reviews-roundup-reaction-cgi-james-mcavoy-sophie-turner-jessica-chastain-a8944706.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |first=Roisin |last=O'Connor |date=June 5, 2019 |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Reviews2\">{{cite web |title=X-Men Dark Phoenix reviews are in: 'Inexplicably boring' |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/x-men-dark-phoenix-reviews-are-in-inexplicably-boring/ |website=[[Cnet]] |first=Jennifer |last=Bisset |date=June 4, 2019 |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ColliderReview\">{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/dark-phoenix-review/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'' Review: The X-Men Franchise Flames Out |last=Goldberg |first=Matt |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=June 4, 2019 |access-date=June 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"40Years\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/dark-phoenix-why-dazzler-took-40-years-to-get-to-the-big-screen/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'': Why Dazzler Took 40 Years to Get to the Big Screen |website=The Wrap |last=Molloy |first=Tim |date=June 6, 2019 |access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<!--  <ref name=\"Ariki\">{{cite web |url=https://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/X-Men-Dark-Phoenix-Cast-46232031 |title=The Entire Cast of X-Men: Dark Phoenix, From Sophie Turner to Michael Fassbender |website=Popsugar |last=Keaney |first=Quinn |date=June 6, 2019 |access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>-->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.foxmovies.com/movies/dark-phoenix}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{X-Men media}}\n{{Marvel Comics films}}\n{{Simon Kinberg}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2010s superhero films]]\n[[Category:2010s prequel films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:2019 3D films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about astronauts]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films about telekinesis]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Lauren Shuler Donner]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Simon Kinberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1992]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Films set on islands]]\n[[Category:Films set on trains]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Simon Kinberg]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Space opera films]]\n[[Category:Superhero films featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:X-Men (film series)]]\n[[Category:2019 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|X-Men: Dark Phoenix|the comic storyline|The Dark Phoenix Saga|the comics characters|Jean Grey|and|Phoenix Force (comics)}}\n{{short description|2019 superhero film directed by Simon Kinberg}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use list-defined references|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dark Phoenix\n| image          = Dark Phoenix (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Simon Kinberg]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Simon Kinberg\n* Hutch Parker\n* [[Lauren Shuler Donner]]\n* Todd Hallowell\n}}\n| writer         = Simon Kinberg\n| based on       = {{Plainlist|\n* {{Based on|[[X-Men]]|[[Stan Lee]]<br />[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n* {{Based on|[[The Dark Phoenix Saga]]|[[Chris Claremont]]<br />[[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]}}\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James McAvoy]]\n* [[Michael Fassbender]]\n* [[Jennifer Lawrence]]\n* [[Nicholas Hoult]]\n* [[Sophie Turner]]\n* [[Tye Sheridan]]\n* [[Alexandra Shipp]]\n* [[Jessica Chastain]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| cinematography = [[Mauro Fiore]]\n| editing        = [[Lee Smith (editor)|Lee Smith]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[20th Century Fox]]\n* [[Marvel Entertainment]]\n* The Donners' Company\n* [[TSG Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = 20th Century Fox\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|6|4|[[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|TCL Chinese Theatre]]|2019|6|7|United States}}\n| runtime        = 114 minutes<ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web |title=''X-Men: Dark Phoenix'' |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/x-men-dark-phoenix-2019 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=May 26, 2019 |access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $200{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"VarietyBudget\" />\n| gross          = $252.4{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=foxmarvel18b.htm |title=Dark Phoenix (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dark Phoenix''''' (also marketed and later released on home media as '''''X-Men: Dark Phoenix''''') is a 2019 American [[superhero film]] based on the [[Marvel Comics]] [[X-Men]] characters. It is a sequel to 2016's ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]'', the seventh mainline installment in the [[X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' film series]] and the twelfth entry in the franchise overall. The film is written and directed by [[Simon Kinberg]] (in his feature directorial debut) and stars an [[ensemble cast]] featuring <!-- CAST ORDER PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK -->[[James McAvoy]], [[Michael Fassbender]], [[Jennifer Lawrence]], [[Nicholas Hoult]], [[Sophie Turner]], [[Tye Sheridan]], [[Alexandra Shipp]], and [[Jessica Chastain]]<!-- CAST ORDER PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK -->. In ''Dark Phoenix'', the X-Men are forced to face the full power of the [[Phoenix Force (comics)|Phoenix]] after a mission in space goes wrong.\n\nAfter ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'' (2014) erased the events of ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'' (2006) from the [[X-Men (film series)|series']] timeline, Kinberg expressed interest in a new adaptation of [[Chris Claremont]] and [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]'s \"[[The Dark Phoenix Saga]]\" in a future film that would be more faithful than his previous attempt with ''The Last Stand'', which was not well received, and even he and writer [[Zak Penn]] were equally unhappy with how it turned out. The new adaptation was confirmed as a follow-up to ''Apocalypse'' in 2016. Kinberg signed on to make his [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]] in June 2017, when the majority of the cast was set to return from ''Apocalypse''. Filming began later that month in [[Montreal]] and was completed in October 2017; the entire third act was later reshot in late 2018, following poor test screenings. The film was dedicated to the memory of ''X-Men'' co-creator [[Stan Lee]], who died in 2018.\n\n''Dark Phoenix'' was theatrically released in the United States on June 7, 2019, by [[20th Century Fox]]. It grossed $252{{nbsp}}million worldwide on a $200-million budget and became the lowest-grossing installment in the series. It also received generally unfavorable reviews from critics with various critical takes; many viewed it as a disappointing and anticlimactic conclusion to Fox's ''X-Men'' series although the performances of the cast and [[Hans Zimmer]]'s score were praised.<ref name=\"Reviews1\" /><ref name=\"Reviews2\" />\n\n== Plot ==\nIn 1975, eight-year-old [[Jean Grey]] and her parents get into a car accident that kills her mother. Shortly afterward, [[Professor X|Professor Charles Xavier]] takes her to [[X-Mansion|Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters]] because her father was afraid of her.\n\nIn 1992, the [[X-Men]] respond to a distress signal from the [[Space Shuttle|space shuttle]] [[Space Shuttle Endeavour|''Endeavour'']], which is critically damaged by solar flare-like energy during the [[STS-49]] mission. While they save the astronauts, Jean is stranded and struck by the energy which she absorbs into her body to save her team's aircraft from destruction. She survives the event, and her psychic powers are greatly amplified as a result, but they become uncontrollable, and she accidentally unleashes her power on mutants celebrating the victory at Xavier's school. Xavier had placed mental walls in Jean's mind as a girl to protect her psychic mind from experiencing trauma; these are destroyed by Jean's enhanced power, and the trauma slowly returns, resulting in her being full of rage and pain. She travels to her childhood hometown after finding out that her father is still alive and learns that he abandoned her. Jean recovers her complete memory of the car accident and remembers that she had inadvertently caused it rendering her mother unconscious at the wheel with her telepathy, which causes her to develop [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]]. The X-Men arrive and attempt to take Jean home, but she uses her power against [[Quicksilver (comics)|Peter Maximoff]] and [[Mystique (comics)|Raven Darkholme]], injuring the former and killing the latter, before fleeing.\n\nJean travels to the mutant refugee island of [[Genosha]] to seek assistance from [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Erik Lehnsherr]] in controlling her rage but is turned away by him after she engages in combat with U.S. military forces tasked with her arrest. Jean meets Vuk, the leader of a shape-shifting alien race known as the [[D'Bari]]. She explains to Jean that she has bonded with [[Phoenix Force (comics)|a force of cosmic power]] that wiped out the D'Bari home planet long ago. The power had consumed all those it came across until it was drawn to Jean. Meanwhile, [[Beast (comics)|Hank McCoy]], mad with grief by Raven's death, allies with Erik and the mutant refugees in an attempt to kill Jean in [[New York City]].\n\nUpon learning of Erik's plan, the X-Men try to stop him and [[Brotherhood of Mutants|his faction of mutants]]. As they battle, Erik manages to enter the building and confront Jean, only to fall to her amplified powers. Xavier then enters the building with [[Nightcrawler (comics)|Kurt Wagner]]. Jean attacks them until Xavier convinces her to read his memories &ndash; allowing her personality to resurface. Feeling remorseful, Jean offers to let Vuk take the force from her; however, it is revealed that doing so would kill Jean, as well as revealing that Vuk also intends to use the force to conquer Earth. Xavier and [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Scott Summers]] are able to prevent Vuk from fully absorbing the force from Jean, though Jean loses consciousness from the ordeal. Troops sent by the U.S. government, who use stun weapons and power-inhibiting collars, attack and subdue both mutant factions, who are placed on a train headed towards a containment facility.\n\nOn the train, Xavier admits to Hank that the latter was right in his earlier accusations of violating Jean's mind. The train is attacked by Vuk and her D'Bari forces. When the soldiers are overpowered by the shape-shifters, the mutants are freed from their restraints to combat the threat. The mutants deal with most of the D'Bari attackers, but Vuk arrives and heads for Jean, defeating each mutant who attempts to stop her. Xavier confers with Jean within his mind, allowing Jean to gain control of her power. After forgiving Xavier, Jean saves the mutants from Vuk's attacks and the ensuing train wreck before proceeding to disintegrate the remaining D'Bari when they attack her. Vuk once again attempts to drain Jean of the force, but Jean takes Vuk into outer space, retakes the power that Vuk had received earlier, and then kills her. Jean then disappears in a burst of energy in the form of a [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]].\n\nIn the aftermath of the incident, Xavier's school is renamed the \"Jean Grey School for Gifted Youngsters\", and Hank becomes their new dean with Xavier having retired. While settling himself in [[Paris]], Xavier is reunited with Erik and agrees to play a game of chess with him. As they start playing, a flaming phoenix appears in the sky.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Tall image|Dark Phoenix cast.jpg|140|1150|The cast of ''Dark Phoenix'' promoting the film at the 2019 [[WonderCon]]. From top to bottom: Hoult, Turner, Sheridan, Shipp, Smit-McPhee, and Peters. (scrollable image)}}\n<!-- Cast and order per closing tombstone credits, roles per closing credits scroll -->\n* [[James McAvoy]] as [[Professor X|Professor Charles Xavier]]: <br />A [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] pacifist, he founded [[X-Mansion|Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters]]. Many of the characters in the film turn against Xavier as some of his decisions regarding Jean Grey's abilities are revealed. Director [[Simon Kinberg]] felt that the character always acts out of concern for the \"greater good,\" though he may make some \"misguided\" choices at times. Kinberg hoped that each character would come across as having \"a valid point of view\" in the film.<ref name=\"KinbergTurnerIGNSep2018\" />\n* [[Michael Fassbender]] as [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Erik Lehnsherr / Magneto]]: <br />Quicksilver's father and a powerful mutant who can control [[magnetic field]]s and manipulate metal, he is Xavier's former best friend and often rival. Magneto has formed a community of mutant refugees on the island of [[Genosha]],<ref name=\"Genosha\" /> which Kinberg compared to [[Israel]] in it being a homeland where mutants can be safe.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" />\n* [[Jennifer Lawrence]] as [[Mystique (comics)|Raven / Mystique]]: <br />A shape-shifting mutant and Xavier's adopted sister. Lawrence described her role in the film as more maternal than before, as she leads the younger X-Men.<ref name=\"EWLawrence\" /> The film continues growing the schism between Mystique and Xavier, with Mystique not approving of some of Xavier's methods, though Kinberg hoped that this would be more subtle in ''Dark Phoenix'' than in previous ''X-Men'' films. The film also sees the character change between appearing as Raven and Mystique more than previously, with each change having a specific meaning to the character and story.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" /> She continues to have feelings for Beast.\n* [[Nicholas Hoult]] as [[Beast (comics)|Hank McCoy / Beast]]: <br />A mutant with a beastly appearance and superhuman physical abilities. He is a teacher at Xavier's School and helps lead the younger X-Men. He continues to have feelings for Mystique.\n* [[Sophie Turner]] as [[Jean Grey]] / [[Phoenix Force (comics)|Phoenix]]: <br />An extremely powerful mutant with telepathic and [[Psychokinesis|telekinetic]] powers who is one of Xavier's most prized students. The [[Phoenix Force (comics)|Phoenix entity]] is unleashed in the film, leading to a fight between the two personalities for control. Turner studied [[dissociative identity disorder]] and [[schizophrenia]] for the role, particularly for scenes where she has to change from the vulnerable Jean to the confident Phoenix.<ref name=\"EWTurner\" /> Kinberg said Turner has the lead role in the film, a first for the actress.<ref name=\"ChastainTHR\" /> Summer Fontana portrays a young Jean Grey.\n* [[Tye Sheridan]] as [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Scott Summers / Cyclops]]: <br />A mutant who fires concussive optic beams. The film develops his relationship with Jean Grey, which Kinberg called \"a huge part of the emotional core of the movie.\" This forces the character to become a leader in the film,<ref name=\"JeanScott\" /> as he is the most prominent character who holds on to hope as Jean grows more unstable.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" />\n* [[Alexandra Shipp]] as [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Ororo Munroe / Storm]]: <br />An African mutant who can control the weather.\n* [[Evan Peters]] as [[Quicksilver (comics)|Peter Maximoff / Quicksilver]]: <br />Magneto's mutant son who can move at [[Speedster (fiction)|superhuman speed]]. Peters described the character as more mature and subdued in the film, being focused on using his abilities for good as a member of the X-Men.<ref name=\"PetersSRMay2018\" />\n* [[Kodi Smit-McPhee]] as [[Nightcrawler (comics)|Kurt Wagner / Nightcrawler]]: <br />A German mutant who can teleport.\n* [[Jessica Chastain]] as Vuk:<br />The leader of a shape-shifting alien race known as the [[D'Bari]] who manipulates the Phoenix. Kinberg described her as \"the devil on Jean's shoulder,\"<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" /> while Chastain called her character \"clinical.\"<ref name=\"EWChastain\" /> Chastain also plays Margaret Smith, the woman Vuk impersonates.\n* [[Scott Shepherd (actor)|Scott Shepherd]] as John Grey\n* [[Ato Essandoh]] as Jones, Vuk's second in command.\n* [[Brian d'Arcy James]] as the [[President of the United States]]\n* [[Halston Sage]] as [[Dazzler (Marvel Comics)|Dazzler]] in the character's first cinematic appearance.<ref name=\"40Years\" />\n* [[Lamar Johnson (actor)|Lamar Johnson]] as [[Match (Marvel Comics)|Match]]\n\nAdditionally, Kota Eberhardt portrays telepath [[Selene (comics)|Selene Gallio]], while [[Andrew Stehlin]] portrays Ariki, a mutant who can utilize his hair braids as a weapon. Hannah Anderson portrays Jean's mother, Elaine. Veteran ''X-Men'' writer [[Chris Claremont]] makes a cameo appearance as a White House guest during the scene when Xavier accepts his award for rescuing the crew of the space shuttle ''Endeavour''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.looper.com/154834/easter-eggs-you-missed-in-x-men-dark-phoenix/ |title=Easter eggs you missed in X-Men: Dark Phoenix: Chris Claremont's cameo |first=Matt |last=Wilson |website=Looper.com |publisher=[[ZergNet]] |access-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAfter joining the 2003 film ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]'', writer [[Zak Penn]] convinced director [[Bryan Singer]] not to adapt the [[Marvel Comics]] storyline \"[[The Dark Phoenix Saga]]\" for the film, believing it was \"too soon to go into the Phoenix story and it was too soon to get cosmic.\"<ref name=\"PennX2\" /> The character of [[Jean Grey|Jean Grey / Phoenix]] was instead explored \"subtly\", with the intention of the full story being adapted in the next film instead.<ref name=\"PennX2\" /><ref name=\"KinbergX3\" /> Singer did not return to direct the sequel, ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'', which was written by Penn and [[Simon Kinberg]]. The studio chose to adapt the \"Dark Phoenix Saga\" as only one of the film's \"parallel storylines\", with an executive at [[20th Century Fox]] suggesting that the \"[[Gifted (comics)|Gifted]]\" storyline also be in that film.<ref name=\"KinbergX3\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comicmix.com/news/2008/04/15/interview-zak-penn-on-the-grand-x-men-fans-and-co-writing-hulk/ |title=INTERVIEW: ZAK PENN ON THE GRAND, X-MEN FANS AND CO-WRITING HULK |access-date=March 18, 2014}}</ref> This version of the story was not well received by fans and critics. Kinberg stated that he and Penn were ultimately unhappy with how the adaptation turned out as well.<ref name=\"RebootJan2016\" />\n\nAfter the timeline of the [[X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' franchise]] was [[retconned]] with the 2014 film ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'', it was noted that a new adaptation of the \"Dark Phoenix Saga\" could be made that ignores the events of ''The Last Stand''. Kinberg and Singer both expressed interest in the prospect, and hinted that 2016's ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]'' would set up elements for a retelling. ''Apocalypse'' introduces [[Sophie Turner]] as a young Jean Grey, and begins exploring \"how powerful she is.\"<ref name=\"RebootJan2016\" /> By April 2016, the sequel to ''Apocalypse'' was believed to indeed re-adapt \"The Dark Phoenix Saga.\"<ref name=\"HHApr2016\" /> In May 2016, Kinberg said that the next ''X-Men'' film after ''Apocalypse'' would be set in the 1990s, advancing one decade, as had been done for each of the previous few ''X-Men'' films.<ref name=\"KinbergMay2016\" /> He also noted that ''Apocalypse'' had introduced younger versions of several characters from the original ''X-Men'' films to give them a new [[origin story]]\u2014including [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]], [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]], [[Nightcrawler (comics)|Nightcrawler]], and Jean Grey\u2014with the intention of then exploring them in their own line of films. He added that he also hoped to see the cast of the previous trilogy of films return, namely [[James McAvoy]] as [[Professor X|Charles Xavier]], [[Michael Fassbender]] as Erik Lehnsherr / Magneto, and [[Jennifer Lawrence]] as [[Mystique (comics)|Raven Darkh\u00f6lme / Mystique]].<ref name=\"CastHopes\" />\n\nIn July, Kinberg said he would begin writing the next mainline ''X-Men'' film \"real soon\".<ref name=\"KinbergJul2016\" /> That November, Fox was said to be pressing \"the reset button\" on the franchise due to the financial and critical under-performance of ''Apocalypse'', with the franchise being reconfigured and Singer not returning to direct the next film. McAvoy, Fassbender, Lawrence, and [[Nicholas Hoult]]'s contracts from the previous trilogy had ended, but Kinberg was optimistically writing the new script with them in mind.<ref name=\"UniversePlans\" /> It was rumored in February 2017 that the next film would be titled ''X-Men: Supernova'', and would begin filming that June.<ref name=\"Supernova\" /> Also in February, Turner confirmed that she would return for the film.<ref name=\"TurnerFeb2017\" /> Kinberg was believed to be interested in making his [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]] with the film,<ref name=\"KinbergDirectFeb2017\" /> and was described as the top contender for the job with interest from Fox. The studio was also looking to negotiate new deals with Lawrence, Fassbender, McAvoy, and Hoult to return.<ref name=\"KinbergDirectFeb20172\" /> By the end of the month, Kinberg described reports that he may direct the film as \"premature,\" but added that if he were to direct, he would not be daunted by the scale of the film due to his experience writing and producing many of the other ''X-Men'' films. He also reiterated that he would adapt \"The Dark Phoenix Saga\" differently to how it was for ''The Last Stand'' if given another opportunity to do so.<ref name=\"KinbergDirectFeb20173\" />\n\n===Writing and original two-part plan===\n\nSimon Kinberg wanted a two-film story, as hinted by Olivia Munn in an interview with Collider in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/olivia-munn-interview-lego-ninjago-movie-x-men-dark-phoenix/|title=Olivia Munn on 'The LEGO Ninjago Movie' & Returning for 'X-Men: Dark Phoenix'|first=Christina|last=Radish|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' later confirmed this initial approach. In late pre-production, the studio canceled the second film, and Kinberg had to make major changes to the first film\u2019s script.<ref name=\"deadline-bomb\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/dark-phoenix-bombs-at-the-box-office-reasons-why-1202629749/|title=\u2018Dark Phoenix\u2019 Bound To Lose $100M+ After Worst Domestic Opening In \u2018X-Men\u2019 Series: Here\u2019s Why|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> Chris Claremont also confirmed the two-film plan and revealed that they would have been titled ''Phoenix'' and ''Dark Phoenix''. The film's purpose, according to Claremont, was to make the audience fall in love with Jean, while the second's purpose was to break their hearts.<ref>https://www.insider.com/dark-phoenix-comic-writer-on-hollywood-movie-adaptations-2019-8</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zLvFSvynDWg</ref>\n\nConcept art revealed that when the movie was titled ''Phoenix'' it was to feature the return of [[Emma Frost]] with a new incarnation of the [[Hellfire Club]]. The new members were [[Harry Leland]], [[Friedrich von Roehm]], [[Fenris (comics)|Fenris]], [[Shinobi Shaw]], and the [[Red Lotus (comics)|Red Lotus]] gang (who Andrew Stehlin was originally set to play).<ref>http://www.cbr.com/dark-phoenix-concept-art-x-men-hellfire-club</ref> When the film was retitled ''Dark Phoenix'', they were replaced with the [[Skrulls]], but later, after reshoots, the D'Bari were chosen as the alien race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2474641/original-dark-phoenix-ending-included-skrulls-and-a-huge-new-york-battle-according-to-tye-sheridan|title=Original Dark Phoenix Ending Included Skrulls And A 'Huge' New York Battle, According To Tye Sheridan|date=June 10, 2019|website=CINEMABLEND}}</ref> The role the aliens play in the story was still based on the Hellfire Club, with Jessica Chastain's character being inspired by Mastermind and Emma Frost.<ref>{{cite web |date= |author1= |title= Jessica Chastain's 'Dark Phoenix' secret character explained |url= https://ew.com/movies/2019/06/07/dark-phoenix-jessica-chastain-character/ |website= [[Entertainment Tonight]] }}</ref> More concept art revealed that the scene with the D\u2019Bari watching Charles Xavier at the White House was an element from ''Phoenix'', as the Hellfire Club can be seen watching the event on television at their lair.<ref>{{cite web |title=F\u00caNIX NEGRA: Artes conceituais mostram cena da ONU e Clube do Inferno! |url=https://universoxmen.com.br/2020/02/fenix-negra-artes-conceituais-mostram-cena-onu-e-clube-do-inferno/ |website=Universo X-Men |language=pt-BR |date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to visual effects supervisor Greg Butler, the story was originally meant to be more cosmic, but that aspect of the Phoenix was meant for the second part of a two-film story.<ref>{{cite web |date= |author1= |title= Dark Phoenix's VFX Supervisor Opens Up About the Astonishing Jean Grey That Could Have Been |url= https://io9.gizmodo.com/dark-phoenixs-vfx-supervisor-opens-up-about-the-astonis-1836850921 |website= io9 }}</ref> In June 2017, it was rumored that the [[Shi'ar]] alien race would be featured in the film,<ref name=\"Shi'ar\" /> and [[Angelina Jolie]] was being looked at for a role, though she was not expected to accept the part. [[Jessica Chastain]] was also potentially being considered for the same character.<ref name=\"JolieChastain\" /> Chastain herself had admitted her character kept constantly changing.<ref>https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/x-men-dark-phoenix-reshot-ending-due-to-similarities-with-another-superhero-movie-exclusive-114022281.html</ref>\n\nSimon Kinberg stated that if he had had four hours to tell the story, he would have included the Hellfire Club and Lilandra.<ref>{{Cite web |first1= Sam |last1= Warner |first2= Rebecca |last2= April May |date= May 30, 2019 |title= Why X-Men: Dark Phoenix removed major elements from comic storyline |url= https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a27650665/x-men-dark-phoenix-why-removed-major-elements-comic-storyline/ |website= [[Digital Spy]] }}</ref>\n\n===Pre-production===\nKinberg said at the start of March 2017 that he and producer Hutch Parker had begun early prep on the film, and that ''Supernova'' was just a code name they had been using for the sequel. He said that they began discussing the story for the film during post-production on ''Apocalypse'', and that they wanted to do \"something bold and radical and expand the universe in the same way that ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' feels bold and radical and certainly ''[[Deadpool (film)|Deadpool]]'' does as well.\"<ref name=\"KinbergMar2017\" /> In pitching the film to the studio, Kinberg used real world imagery such as footage of disasters or lightning strikes, and focused on an organic and relevant approach as a response to criticisms of ''Apocalypse''{{'}}s heightened reality.<ref name=\"EWKinberg\" /> Fox officially titled the film ''Dark Phoenix'' in April 2017, and gave it a release date of November 2, 2018.<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\" /> Fassbender indicated in May that he would be returning for the film,<ref name=\"FassbenderMay2017\" /> and Parker soon hinted that a younger version of the character [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] could appear, and that the film could possibly explore the cosmic elements of the \"Dark Phoenix\" storyline.<ref name=\"ParkerRogue\" /><ref name=\"ParkerCosmic\" />\n\nFox confirmed that Kinberg would direct the film, and that McAvoy, Fassbender, Lawrence, and Hoult had all signed on to return for one more film. In addition to Turner, ''Apocalypse'' actors [[Alexandra Shipp]], [[Tye Sheridan]], and [[Kodi Smit-McPhee]] were also confirmed to be returning, while producers for the film were revealed to be Kinberg and Parker. At that time, Chastain was in talks to join the cast as Shi'ar Empress [[Lilandra Neramani|Lilandra]], the film's villain. The film's script was said to \"hew closer\" to the original \"Dark Phoenix Saga\" by [[Chris Claremont]] and [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] than ''The Last Stand'' did.<ref name=\"FormalizedPlans\" /><ref name=\"FormalizedPlans2\" /> Despite being initially listed as a producer, [[Lauren Shuler Donner]] had no involvement in the film and was only given credit due to contract terms.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/x-men-dark-phoenix-jennifer-lawrence-michael-fassbender-james-mcavoy-simon-kinberg-1202113290/ |title=Fox Formalizes Simon Kinberg To Helm ''X-Men: Dark Phoenix''; Jennifer Lawrence, Michael Fassbender, James McAvoy Back, Jessica Chastain In Talks |date=June 14, 2017 |work=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kit |first=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/we-were-wrong-behind-dark-phoenix-foxs-dismal-x-men-franchise-finale-plans-1216859 |title=\"We Were Wrong\": Behind Fox's ''Dark Phoenix'' Debacle |date=June 10, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> It was later revealed that the character [[Dazzler (Marvel Comics)|Dazzler]] would appear in the film, after being hinted at in a scene that was eventually deleted from ''Apocalypse''.<ref name=\"Dazzler\" /> [[Halston Sage]] was cast in the role in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pearson |first=Ben |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/halston-sage-x-men/ |title=''X-Men: Dark Phoenix'' May Have Cast a ''Paper Towns'' Actress as Dazzler |date=August 15, 2017 |work=/Film |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> Singer was originally announced as being a producer on the film, but following [[Bryan Singer#Sexual abuse allegations|allegations of sexual abuse]] against Singer, Kinberg stated that he was not involved in the film and his name would not be in the film's credits.<ref name=\"ChastainTHR\" />\n\nDaniel Orlandi returned as costume designer for the film after doing so on ''Logan'',<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" /><ref name=\"Orlandi\" /> and worked with Kinberg to come up with costumes for the X-Men that were closer to the original comic designs that Kinberg had wanted to see in the films since he first joined the franchise, but had never been in a position to control before. The final costumes for the film feature the yellow-and-blue design of the original comics, but combine features of designs from many different incarnations of the group. Kinberg also looked to ''Logan'' for general design inspiration, wanting to replicate the \"naturalistic\" and \"handmade\" quality of that film for the costumes, sets, props, and title design. He felt that this would give more impact to the large-scale elements of the film, and help it be more emotional, comparing this idea to the original ''[[Star Wars]]'' films.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on June 28, 2017, in [[Montreal]], Quebec,<ref name=\"FormalizedPlans\" /><ref name=\"ACTRAFilming\" /> under the [[working title]] ''Teen Spirit''.<ref name=\"WorkingTitle\" /> [[Mauro Fiore]] served as cinematographer.<ref name=\"Fiore\" /> Filming primarily took place at MELS Studios.<ref name=\"LaPresseReshoots\" /> Before the end of the month, [[Evan Peters]] was set to reprise his role as \"audience favorite\" character [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] from the previous films, and [[Lamar Johnson (actor)|Lamar Johnson]] joined the cast in an undisclosed role.<ref name=\"PetersJohnson\" /> At the start of August, Chastain confirmed her involvement in the film;<ref name=\"ChastainConfirmed\" /> she was interested in the story, after turning down roles in other superhero films, due to its focus on female characters.<ref name=\"XWomen\" /> Kinberg said he wanted the film to be \"human\" and emotional like previous ''X-Men'' films, and that he was looking to ground the \"Dark Phoenix Saga\" story for his adaptation \"so it's not too intergalactic.\"<ref name=\"KinbergTFAug2017\" /> He later clarified that the film would still include alien characters as in the comic storyline, an element that was ignored for the ''Last Stand'' adaptation but which he felt was integral to the story.<ref name=\"KinbergETMay2018\" /><ref name=\"KinbergTurnerIGNSep2018\" /> He also said that the film would tonally be less operatic than previous ''X-Men'' films, which he hoped would make it more relatable for audiences.<ref name=\"KinbergETMay2018\" /> By September, [[Daniel Cudmore]] had stated that he would be appearing in the film, but could not confirm whether he would be reprising his role as [[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]] from previous films in the franchise.<ref name=\"CudmoreSep2017\" /> Chastain revealed that she was not actually playing Lilandra.<ref name=\"NoLilandra\" /> While [[Olivia Munn]] had initially said that she would reprise her role as [[Psylocke]]<!-- , and described ''Dark Phoenix'' as \"a two parter\" -->,<ref name=\"Munn\" /> by February 2019, she revealed that she was unable to reprise her role due to scheduling conflicts with filming ''[[The Predator (film)|The Predator]]''.<ref name=\"NoPsylocke\" /> Filming was completed on October 14, 2017.<ref name=\"ACTRAFilming\" /><ref name=\"FilmingEnds\" />\n\n===Post-production===\nIn December 2017, Kinberg revealed that the film would be in post-production for almost a year, longer than usual for the series, because he wanted to take the time to have the visual effects look right by focusing on the \"nuance\" of the effects rather than the scale.<ref name=\"EWVisuals\" /> He also explained that he \"felt in his gut\" that this was the story that he needed to tell once Singer left the franchise, and that his vision for the film was \"so clear in my head, emotionally and visually, that it would have killed me to hand this to somebody else to direct.\" The film was described as being the most sinister and somber of the franchise, with McAvoy finding it to be the most emotional of the ''X-Men'' films he had worked on. It becomes a \"fight for Jean's soul\" and features a twist that was intended to have significant repercussions on the entire franchise.<ref name=\"EWCover\" /> Lawrence revealed that she had worked to convince Kinberg to direct the film, and had promised to return for it if he did so, despite her dislike of the make-up required to portray her character.<ref name=\"EWLawrence2\" /> It was also revealed then that the film would introduce a version of the island [[Genosha]], adapted to the film as a mutant refuge led by Magneto;<ref name=\"Genosha\" /> and that it would focus on the female characters more so than previous films in the series, particularly Jean Grey as both the protagonist and antagonist of the film, and Chastain's character, with whom Grey has a complex relationship.<ref name=\"XWomen\" />\n\nFox delayed the film's release in March 2018, pushing it back from November 2, 2018 to February 14, 2019.<ref name=\"Mar2018ReleaseDelay\" /> This was because Fox and Kinberg wanted to schedule some routine reshoots for the film after receiving feedback from audiences during a test screening, but were not able to get all of the necessary cast members together until August or September 2018. This would not have left enough time to complete post-production work such as visual effects for the additional footage before the November 2018 release date.<ref name=\"ColliderReshoots\" /> Specifically, Kinberg was looking to rework the third act of the film, and re-wrote part of the script ahead of the reshoots. With post-production already underway, the film was believed to have been under-budget, while the planned reshoots would cost less than $10{{nbsp}}million. Additionally, Kinberg and the studio had been looking to change the film's release date for \"some time\" to avoid competing with the Christmas-oriented film ''[[The Nutcracker and the Four Realms]]''. The new February release date was noted as having the film opening away from other major studio films, while placing it on [[President's Day]] weekend, which had proved to be successful for ''Deadpool'' and Marvel's ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''.<ref name=\"THRReshoots\" /> Addressing the reshoots, Kinberg confirmed the scheduling delays, and described the photography as a \"normal\" part of the film's creation that would allow him \"enough time to have it ready and looking perfect.\"<ref name=\"KinbergReshoots\" />\n\nAt the end of April, a Fox panel at the 2018 CinemaCon revealed the first logo for the film. It did not include \"''X-Men''\" in the title, but included a circle around the 'X' in ''Dark Phoenix'' which was compared to the ''[[The X-Files|X-Files]]'' logo;<ref name=\"FirstLogo\" /> the film was later confirmed to be simply titled ''Dark Phoenix'' in the United States, and ''X-Men: Dark Phoenix'' for release internationally.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" /> By that August, the reshoots were expected to take place in Montreal over two-and-a-half weeks, though the Quebec Film and Television Bureau believed that these reshoots would take up to three months to complete, due to scheduling conflicts among the cast members.<ref name=\"LaPresseReshoots\" /><ref name=\"ColliderReshootsAug2018\" /> The reshoots were set to take place at MTL Grand\u00e9 studios since MELS Studios was reserved for another production during the reshoot period,<ref name=\"LaPresseReshoots\" /> and had begun by August 31.<ref name=\"ReshootsBegin\" /> At the end of September, after the release of the film's first trailer, Fox again delayed the film's release, setting it for June 7, 2019. This date was seen as a better time to release the film in China, where the trailer received more attention than in the United States, while also allowing it to take advantage of premium screens that had previously been reserved for Fox's newly-delayed and later canceled ''[[Gambit (unproduced film)|Gambit]]'' film.<ref name=\"Sep2018ReleaseDelay\" /><ref name=\"DisneyMay2019ScheduleUpdate\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/gambit-movie-dead/ |title=\u2018Gambit\u2019 Is Dead; Disney Drops the X-Men Spinoff from the Schedule |website=[[Collider]] |last=Goldberg |first=Matt |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |archive-url=http://www.webcitation.org/78CX9lkfJ |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The move was also reportedly to appease [[James Cameron]], who had ''[[Alita: Battle Angel]]'' moved from December to February and did not want competition from another Fox would-be blockbuster; Kinberg and ''Dark Phoenix'' producers opposed the change as the film was not made for a summer and was facing heavy competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"We Were Wrong\": Behind Fox's ''Dark Phoenix'' Debacle |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=June 10, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/heat-vision/we-were-wrong-behind-dark-phoenix-foxs-dismal-x-men-franchise-finale-plans-1216859 |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Lana Condor]] revealed that she was unable to return as [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]] due to her commitment to the film ''[[To All the Boys I've Loved Before (film)|To All the Boys I've Loved Before]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"CondorCollider\" /> [[Lee Smith (editor)|Lee Smith]] serves as editor for the film.<ref name=\"EditorSmith\" /> Visual effects were provided by [[Moving Picture Company|MPC]], MELS, [[Rising Sun Pictures]], [[Rodeo FX]], [[Scanline VFX]] and Soho VFX, with Phil Brennan serving as the main visual effects supervisor.<ref name=\"VisualEffects\" />\n\n==Music==\nEvan Peters stated in January 2018 that [[Hans Zimmer]] was composing the score for the film,<ref name=\"Zimmer\" /> despite Zimmer having said in March 2016 that he would not score another superhero film following his experience working on ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''.<ref name=\"ZimmerNoSupers\" /> Zimmer later explained that in conversations with director [[Ron Howard]] he was convinced to not keep a \"blanket\" view, and to focus on waiting for the right story rather than avoiding an entire genre. When Kinberg approached him at a concert to talk about his vision for ''Dark Phoenix'', Zimmer realized that the story was one that he wanted to help tell, and that the film was an opportunity for something that he had always wanted to try in a film score; he decided to join the production.<ref name=\"ZimmerExplanation\" /> In writing the film's score, Zimmer wrote new themes for the X-Men, Magneto, and the Phoenix, and chose to omit previously established themes written by previous composer [[John Ottman]].\n\nOn May 23, 2019, the track \"Extraordinary Being\" by [[Emeli Sand\u00e9]] was released as the official soundtrack.<ref>{{Cite AV Media |last=EmeliSandeVEVO |title=Emeli Sand\u00e9 - Extraordinary Being \u2013 In Collaboration with X-Men: Dark Phoenix |date=May 23, 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NnYsk7jfUTE |via= [[YouTube]] |access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> The soundtrack was released digitally on June 7. A second album, entitled ''Xperiments from Dark Phoenix'', containing previously unreleased suites and themes written for the film was announced on July 25.<ref>{{Citation |title=Hans Zimmer's ''Xperiments from Dark Phoenix'' to Be Released |date=July 25, 2019 |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/07/25/hans-zimmers-xperiments-from-dark-phoenix-to-be-released/ |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Originally planned to be released as the second disk of a two-CD set, a fan-led petition to Fox Music was made when it appeared the material would not be released. Zimmer later revealed in an interview with Scala Radio that over 16 hours of music was written for the film, and that he was fighting to get a second disk released after the critical and financial failure of the film.<ref>{{Cite AV Media |title=Hans Zimmer with Mark Kermode on Scala Radio |date=July 20, 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mHmKZbUZiIA |via= [[YouTube]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> The album was released digitally on August 2, 2019.\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Dark Phoenix: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = film\n| artist     = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| cover      = Darkphoenixhanszimmer.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2019|06|07}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 67:55\n| label      = [[Fox Music]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Widows (2018 film)|Widows]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = [[The Lion King (2019 soundtrack)|The Lion King: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline      = Track listing\n| total_length = 67:55\n| title1       = Gap\n| length1      = 8:07\n| title2       = Dark\n| length2      = 4:27\n| title3       = Frameshift\n| length3      = 8:15\n| title4       = Amity\n| length4      = 5:52\n| title5       = Intimate\n| length5      = 10:14\n| title6       = Negative\n| length6      = 3:58\n| title7       = Deletion\n| length7      = 4:51\n| title8       = Reckless\n| length8      = 9:35\n| title9       = Insertion\n| length9      = 7:56\n| title10      = Coda\n| length10     = 4:40\n}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Xperiments from Dark Phoenix\n| type         = film\n| artist       = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| cover        = Xperimentsfromdp.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|2019|08|02}}\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film score]]\n| length       = 78:43\n| label        = [[Remote Control Productions (American company)|Remote Control Productions]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[The Lion King (2019 soundtrack)|The Lion King: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year    = 2019\n| next_title   = [[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge on the Run]]\n| next_year    = 2020\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline      = Track listing\n| total_length = 78:43\n| title1       = X-HZT\n| length1      = 17:27\n| title2       = X-X\n| length2      = 5:59\n| title3       = X-LGDP\n| length3      = 8:07\n| title4       = X-SI\n| length4      = 6:25\n| title5       = X-HD\n| length5      = 3:32\n| title6       = X-MP\n| length6      = 3:21\n| title7       = X-MT\n| length7      = 5:03\n| title8       = X-TX\n| length8      = 8:48\n| title9       = X-MDP\n| length9      = 9:06\n| title10      = X-F\n| length10     = 3:56\n| title11      = X-CH\n| length11     = 4:58\n| title12      = X-SS\n| length12     = 2:01\n}}\n\n== Marketing ==\n[[File:Dark Phoenix cast by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|300px|(L:R) Writer-director [[Simon Kinberg]], producer Hutch Parker, and stars [[Sophie Turner]], [[Tye Sheridan]], [[Nicholas Hoult]], [[Alexandra Shipp]], [[Evan Peters]], and [[Kodi Smit-McPhee]] promoting ''Dark Phoenix'' at the 2019 [[WonderCon]].]]\nTurner revealed the first trailer for ''Dark Phoenix'' on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' on September 26, 2018, before Fox released it online. Responses to the trailer widely considered it to be too similar to ''X-Men: The Last Stand''.<ref name=\"TrailerResponses\" /> Graeme McMillan and Aaron Couch of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that this feeling could have been avoided if the trailer had shown more of the film's space and alien elements, which would have differentiated it from the ''Last Stand'' adaptation.<ref name=\"THRTrailer\" /> Scott Mendelson at ''[[Forbes]]'' called the trailer \"dull,\" and said that its focusing on the characters rather than big effects or action was a risk by Fox, given that audiences have indicated through the box office numbers of ''X-Men: Apocalypse'' that they are not necessarily interested in this version of the ''X-Men'' characters.<ref name=\"ForbesTrailer\" /> The trailer was watched 8{{nbsp}}million times within 24 hours on Fox's [[YouTube]] channel, but received 44{{nbsp}}million views within that same time period across Chinese social media platforms, leading to Fox re-focusing their release plans on China.<ref name=\"Sep2018ReleaseDelay\" />\n\nA second trailer was released on February 27, 2019, followed by a third and final trailer on April 17.\n\nOn March 2019, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' had reported that the film faced promotional difficulties as long-term employees on the marketing team vacated as the result of lay-offs from the merger with Disney. They reported that a Fox marketing executive said: \"We know when we are dropping a trailer, but we are nowhere near where we should be at this time. It's frightening. I would be mad if I were a filmmaker.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/03/inside-hollywoods-disney-fox-freakout|title=Inside Hollywood's Disney-Fox Freakout|first=Nicole|last=Sperling|website= [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] }}</ref> Similar reports were made after the film's release, with ''The Hollywood Reporter'' stating that it resulted in the film having less awareness rates than any other film in the series based on a NRG tracking poll taken in May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/we-were-wrong-behind-dark-phoenix-foxs-dismal-x-men-franchise-finale-plans-1216859|title=\"We Were Wrong\": Behind Fox's 'Dark Phoenix' Debacle|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' also reported that they too heard of the marketing campaign being in disarray since February and cited it as a major factor to the film's financial failure. They also report that Disney had attempted to integrate the film into their marketing but did not have enough time, which Simon Kinberg had confirmed in a KCRW podcast.<ref name=\"deadline-bomb\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrw.com/culture/shows/the-business/director-simon-kinberg-on-the-dark-fate-of-dark-phoenix/the-business-exclusive-simon-kinberg-on-the-dark-fate-of-dark-phoenix|title=The Business exclusive: Simon Kinberg on the dark fate of \u2018Dark Phoenix\u2019|website=KCRW}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2019, the official video of the soundtrack ''Extraordinary Being'' by [[Emeli Sand\u00e9]] was released, showing moments from the film.<ref>{{Cite AV Media |last=EmeliSandeVEVO |title=Emeli Sand\u00e9 - Extraordinary Being \u2013 In Collaboration with X-Men: Dark Phoenix |date=May 23, 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NnYsk7jfUTE |via= [[YouTube]] |access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Dark Phoenix'' was released in the United States on June 7, 2019. It was previously slated for November 2, 2018,<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\" /> then rescheduled to be released on February 14, 2019,<ref name=\"Mar2018ReleaseDelay\" /> before being pushed to June.<ref name=\"Sep2018ReleaseDelay\" /> It is known as ''X-Men: Dark Phoenix'' for release in countries outside of the United States.<ref name=\"KinbergEmpireBreakdown\" /> The film is distributed by 20th Century Fox.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |last2=Lang |first2=Brent |title=Fox Feels the Pressure From Disney as Film Flops Mount |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/fox-disney-earnings-dark-phoenix-stuber-racing-in-the-rain-1203300260/ |access-date=September 4, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |agency=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=August 13, 2019}}</ref> The film held its world premiere at the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|TCL Chinese Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], California on June 4, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/scene/news/famke-janssen-dark-pheonix-sophie-turner-xmen-1203234101/ |title=Famke Janssen on Sophie Turner in ''Dark Phoenix'' and Whether She Would Return to the ''X-Men'' Franchise |last=Jackson |first=Angelique |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 5, 2019 |access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Dark Phoenix'' was released in the US on [[Digital distribution|digital download]] by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] on September 3, 2019, and was released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on September 17. It is the first title released by TCFHE after the Disney purchase of Fox.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/07/16/x-men-dark-phoenix-blu-ray-release-date/ |title=X-Men: Dark Phoenix Release Date |website=Comicbook.com |date=July 16, 2019 |access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> For home media releases, the film was titled ''X-Men: Dark Phoenix''.<ref>https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn%3AANd9GcRZuoXNUHvP_P_XDuS60shXqPjQKq93ZkSLTQASYlquEqHLjg8_</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Dark Phoenix'' has grossed $65.8{{nbsp}}million in the United States and Canada, and $186.6{{nbsp}}million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $252.4{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /> Based on its global opening, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' estimated the film would lose the studio $100\u2013120&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/dark-phoenix-bombs-at-the-box-office-reasons-why-1202629749/|title=''Dark Phoenix'' Bound To Lose $100M+ After Worst Domestic Opening In ''X-Men'' Series: Here's Why|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=June 9, 2019|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Dark Phoenix'' was released alongside ''[[The Secret Life of Pets 2]]'', and was initially projected to gross $50\u201360{{nbsp}}million from 3,721 theaters in its opening weekend, with the studio expecting a $50-million debut.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/secret-life-of-pets-2-dark-phoenix-box-office-preview/ |title=''Secret Life of Pets 2'' and ''Dark Phoenix'' Vie for Top Spot in Crowded Box Office |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=June 4, 2019 |access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyBudget\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/box-office/box-office-dark-phoenix-secret-life-of-pets-2-opening-weekend-1203232810/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'' Takes on ''Secret Life of Pets 2'' in Summer Box Office Battle |last=Rubin |first=Rebecca |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 5, 2019 |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> However, after making $14{{nbsp}}million on its first day (including $5{{nbsp}}million from Thursday night previews, the lowest ''X-Men'' total since [[The Wolverine (film)|''The Wolverine'']]'s $4{{nbsp}}million in 2013), projections were lowered to $34{{nbsp}}million. It ended up debuting to $32.8{{nbsp}}million, finishing second, behind ''The Secret Life of Pets 2''. It was the lowest total of the franchise by $20{{nbsp}}million and the first time an ''X-Men'' film did not top the box office the week of its release.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/dark-phoenix-secret-life-of-pets-2-weekend-box-office-1202628724/ |title=''Secret Life of Pets 2'' Seeing $47M+, But ''Dark Phoenix'' Up in Smoke With in Lowest Opening For ''X-Men'' Movie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=June 9, 2019 |access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> In its second weekend, the film fell 73% to $7.3{{nbsp}}million, finishing fourth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/men-in-black-international-shaft-secret-life-of-pets-2-weekend-box-office-1202632705/|title=''Men in Black: International'' Domestic Passport Revoked With $26M Opening, ''Shaft'' Drops His Gun With $7M+: Summer Sequelitis, Here We Go Again|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=June 16, 2019 |access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref> The following weekend the film was pulled from 1,667 theaters and made $3.5{{nbsp}}million, finishing tenth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-opening-weekend-box-office-childs-play-1202635964/|title=\u2018Toy Story 4\u2019: Disney Leaves Money on the Table Stateside With $118M Debut, But Grabs $238M Global Opening Record For Animated Pic|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=June 23, 2019|access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn other territories, the film was projected to gross $120\u2013135{{nbsp}}million, including $50\u201360{{nbsp}}million from China, for a global debut of around $170{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/dark-phoenix-to-rise-above-secret-life-of-pets-2-in-170m-global-debut-1202627515/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'' To Rise Above ''Secret Life of Pets 2'' In $170M+ Global Debut |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first1=Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro |first2=Nancy |last2=Tartaglione |date=June 5, 2019 |access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> The film made $13{{nbsp}}million on its first day in China (including previews). It ended up debuting to just $103.7{{nbsp}}million internationally and $136.5{{nbsp}}million worldwide. Its largest markets were China ($45.6{{nbsp}}million), South Korea ($5.1{{nbsp}}million), Mexico ($5{{nbsp}}million) and the United Kingdom ($4.9{{nbsp}}million).<ref name=\"DeadlineINT\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/dark-phoenix-rises-in-china-with-12m-launch-day-are-dark-times-ahead-overseas-1202628273/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'' Ashen With $107M Overseas Debut; ''Aladdin'' Tops $600M WW \u2013 International Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |date=June 9, 2019 |access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 23% based on 352 reviews, with an average rating of 4.63/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Dark Phoenix'' ends an era of the ''X-Men'' franchise by taking a second stab at adapting a classic comics arc\u2014with deeply disappointing results.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_phoenix/|title=Dark Phoenix (2019) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> It is the lowest-rated installment ''X-Men'' film on the website.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/franchise/x_men/ |title=X-Men Franchise Scores |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 43 out of 100, based on 52 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-phoenix |title=Dark Phoenix Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |access-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale and those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an overall positive score of 69% (with an average 3 out of 5 stars) and a 49% \"definite recommend.\"<ref name=\"opening\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[TheWrap]]'', William Bibbiani said of the film: \"It would be wonderful to report that ''Dark Phoenix'' was an impressive send-off to this long-running franchise... Instead it's just a disappointingly average superhero flick, with a familiar story, disinterested actors, some cool action sequences, and a whole lot of missed opportunities.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/dark-phoenix-film-review-x-men-2019/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'' Film Review: X-Men Saga Wraps Up With Overly Familiar, Mediocre Sequel |last=Bibbani |first=William |date=June 4, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 1.5 out of 4 stars and said, \"It's hard to even render an opinion on the discrete strengths and weaknesses of a franchise that has devolved to the point of ''Dark Phoenix'', a lavishly brutal chore nearly as violent as the Wolverine movie ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' and a movie featuring more death by impalement and whirling metal than all the ''[[Saw (franchise)|Saw]]'' movies put together.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-dark-phoenix-x-men-movie-review-0604-story.html |title=''Dark Phoenix'' review: \"X-Men\" mutant doesn't start the fire |last=Phillips |first=Michael |date=June 4, 2019 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=June 4, 2019 |author-link=Michael Phillips (critic)}}</ref>\n\nMatt Goldberg of ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]'' gave the film a grade of \"D\" and wrote, \"When Marvel Studios inevitably reboots ''X-Men'', a movie like ''Dark Phoenix'' will be a forgotten relic. The characters and their world deserve better, but we'll have to wait until their next evolution.\"<ref name=\"ColliderReview\" /> [[Kurt Loder]] of ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine wrote, \"There are several things wrong with ''Dark Phoenix''. I'm tempted to say everything is wrong with it, except that the picture is largely in focus and the credits appear to be correctly spelled. Other than that, though...\"<ref name=\"R\">{{Cite web |url=https://reason.com/2019/06/07/review-dark-phoenix/ |title=Review: Dark Phoenix |author-link=Kurt Loder |first=Kurt |last=Loder |date=June 7, 2019 |work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref> Rodrigo Perez of ''The Playlist'' said: \"Its atrocious, expository dialogue, cumbersome plot, whiplashing character motivations, unintentionally funny moments, and often corny costumes ensure ''Dark Phoenix'' will be remembered in the annals of mediocre movies.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theplaylist.net/dark-phoenix-xmen-review-20190605/ |title=''Dark Phoenix'': Gaslighting, Bad Men & Ideas of Identity & Destiny Can't Save This Clumsy ''X-Men'' Movie [Review] |last=Perez |first=Rodrigo |date=June 5, 2019 |website=The Playlist |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConversely, [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']]'s [[Owen Gleiberman]] summarized his positive review with, \"The ''X-Men'' franchise wraps up... with a functionally plotted sequel that attains a note of ominous majesty, thanks to Sophie Turner's presence as an X-Woman consumed by the awesomeness of her power.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/dark-phoenix-review-sophie-turner-james-mcavoy-jennifer-lawrence-1203231826/ |title=Film Review: ''Dark Phoenix'' |last=Glieberman |first=Owen |author-link=Owen Glieberman |date=June 5, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKinberg took responsibility for the film's poor reception, stating, \"I'm here, I'm saying when a movie doesn't work, put it on me. I'm the writer-director, the movie didn't connect with audiences, that's on me.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcrw.com/culture/shows/the-business/director-simon-kinberg-on-the-dark-fate-of-dark-phoenix/the-business-exclusive-simon-kinberg-on-the-dark-fate-of-dark-phoenix |title=The Business exclusive: Simon Kinberg on the dark fate of \u2018Dark Phoenix\u2019 |last=Masters |first=Kim |website=KCRW |date=June 14, 2019 |access-date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was nominated for two [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] but didn\u2019t win any of them. It was nominated in the category [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel|Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel]], and Jessica Chastain was nominated as [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]].<ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.razzies.com/razz-newz.html|title=RAZZ NEWZ - The Razzies!|website=razzies.com}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n===Sequels===\nKinberg said in May 2016 that ''Dark Phoenix'' will be the first in a new trilogy focusing on the younger versions of the original ''X-Men'' characters.<ref name=\"CastHopes\" />\n\n===Marvel Cinematic Universe===\nAfter the [[acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney]] was announced in December 2017, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] stated that any future ''X-Men'' films would be produced by [[Marvel Studios]] as part of the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]], with the X-Men franchise being melded with the MCU.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"DisneyTHR\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/x-men-hit-marvel-cinematic-universe-at-2021-1195846 |title=X-Men Franchise Poised for Shake-Up as Fox's Marvel Heroes Migrate to Disney |last=Couch |first=Aaron |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 20, 2019 |access-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"KinbergX3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ifmagazine.com/feature.asp?article=1525 |title=Exclusive Interview: Screenwriter Simon Kinberg Talks X-Men: The Last Stand \u2013 Part 1 |last=Elliot |first=Sean |work=[[Electric Entertainment|iF Magazine]] |date=June 8, 2006 |access-date=December 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617005244/http://www.ifmagazine.com/feature.asp?article=1525 |archive-date=June 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RebootJan2016\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Rebooting-Dark-Phoenix-Saga-Here-What-Simon-Kinberg-Says-106727.html |title=Rebooting The Dark Phoenix Saga? Here's What Simon Kinberg Says |last=Romano |first=Nick |work=Cinema Blend |date=January 21, 2016 |access-date=June 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6rWJDYbvl?url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Rebooting-Dark-Phoenix-Saga-Here-What-Simon-Kinberg-Says-106727.html |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"HHApr2016\">{{cite web |url=http://heroichollywood.com/next-x-men-post-apocalypse-dark-phoenix-saga/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: The Next X-Men Film Post ''X-Men: Apocalypse'' |last=Gonzalez |first=Umberto |work=Heroic Hollywood |date=April 16, 2016 |access-date=June 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6rWJHAonO?url=http://heroichollywood.com/next-x-men-post-apocalypse-dark-phoenix-saga/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-sta